Websites are systems that allow users to access content over the Internet using a browser. They rely on multiple technologies working together, including DNS, HTTP/HTTPS, web servers, and browsers.
When you visit a website, your device communicates with a server to request and display information.

Step-by-Step Process:

When you enter a URL like www.example.com, the following happens:

1. DNS Lookup
Your browser first uses DNS to translate the domain name into an IP address.
Example: example.com → 93.184.216.34

2. Establishing a Connection
Once the IP address is known, your browser connects to the web server using HTTP or HTTPS.
If HTTPS is used:
A secure encrypted connection is created using TLS

3. HTTP Request
Your browser sends an HTTP request to the server asking for the webpage.

This request may include:

Requested page (e.g. /index.html)
Browser information
Cookies or session data

4. Server Response
The web server processes the request and sends back a response.
This response usually contains:

HTML (structure of the page)
CSS (styling)
JavaScript (interactivity)

5. Browser Rendering
Your browser processes the response and builds the webpage:

HTML defines structure
CSS defines appearance
JavaScript adds functionality

The final result is what you see on your screen.

Key Components of a Website:

Web Browser
Software used to access websites (Chrome, Firefox, Edge).

Web Server
A system that stores and delivers website content.

DNS
Translates domain names into IP addresses.

HTTP/HTTPS
Protocols used for communication between browser and server.

Static vs Dynamic Websites

Static Websites:
Fixed content
Same for every user
Simple HTML/CSS pages

Dynamic Websites:
Content changes based on user or database
Uses server-side processing (e.g. login systems, dashboards)

Why does thys matter in cybersecurity?
Understanding how websites work is important because many attacks target web infrastructure, such as:

Phishing websites
SQL injection
Session hijacking
Man-in-the-middle attacks
Broken authentication

Key Takeaways:
Websites work through a combination of DNS, HTTP, and web servers.
Browsers request data and servers respond with content.
Pages are built using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.
HTTPS adds encryption for security.
Web applications are common targets for cyberattacks.
